03911nam a22005055i 9780674985247DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749852477 a10.4159/97806749852472doi  a(DE-B1597)500396  a(OCoLC)1024312642  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a940.5314509729821 aJennings, Eric T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEscape from Vichy :bThe Refugee Exodus to the French Caribbean /cEric T. Jennings. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b21 halftones, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. Undesirables -- t2. Opening the Martinique Corridor -- t3. Understanding the Martinique Route -- t4. The Crossings -- t5. Wartime Martinique -- t6. Snake Charmers in a Viper’s Nest -- t7. Surrealism Meets Negritude -- t8. The Window Closes -- tEpilogue -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early years of World War II, thousands of political refugees traveled from France to Vichy-controlled Martinique in the French Caribbean, en route to what they hoped would be safer shores in North, Central, and South America. While awaiting transfer from the colony, the exiles formed influential ties—with one another and with local black dissidents. Escape from Vichy recounts this flight from the refugees’ perspectives, using novels, unpublished diaries, archives, memoirs, artwork, and other materials to explore the unlikely encounters that fueled an anti-fascist artistic and intellectual movement. The refugees included Spanish Republicans, anti-Nazi Germans and Austrians, anti-fascist Italians, Jews from across Europe, and others fleeing violence and repression. They were met with hostility by the Vichy government and rejection by the nations where they hoped to settle. Martinique, however, provided a site propitious for creative ferment, where the revolutionary Victor Serge conversed with the anthropologist Claude Lévi-Strauss, and the Surrealist André Breton met Negritude thinkers René Ménil and Aimé and Suzanne Césaire. As Eric T. Jennings shows, these interactions gave rise to a rich current of thought celebrating blackness and rejecting racism. What began as expulsion became a kind of rescue, cut short by Washington’s fears that wolves might be posing in sheep’s clothing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aPolitical refugeeszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical refugeeszMartiniquexHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xRefugeeszMartinique. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zFrancezMarseille. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674985247423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674985247.jpg  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles